7
00:00:33,222 --> 00:00:35,883
Are any of you familiar with the video game Puzzle Fighter, by chance?

8
00:00:36,143 --> 00:00:37,743
Anyone? Yeah, a lot of you. Okay, great.

9
00:00:37,763 --> 00:00:42,425
So I'm going to tell you my thoughts on these two games

10
00:00:42,585 --> 00:00:44,186
and why I would ever put them together

11
00:00:44,326 --> 00:00:47,527
and what happens when you do and what some of my design goals were

12
00:00:48,087 --> 00:00:50,448
and a little bit about how the strategy of the game works

13
00:00:50,688 --> 00:00:52,688
and then some of the design problems that I had.

14
00:00:53,229 --> 00:00:58,471
along the way. So let's start with Puzzle Fighter. So in this video game, on

15
00:00:58,951 --> 00:01:03,773
your side of the screen, gems will fall and you put them together into big gems and then you

16
00:01:04,693 --> 00:01:08,054
break them and send them to the other side. And when you fill up the other side of the screen,

17
00:01:08,074 --> 00:01:13,076
the opponent's side, then you win. And that is a pretty standard thing.

18
00:01:13,096 --> 00:01:17,458
It works the same way in other puzzle games like Puzzle Bobble or Tetris.

19
00:01:18,412 --> 00:01:23,215
But in my opinion, Puzzle Fighter really stands head and shoulders above all the other puzzle

20
00:01:23,235 --> 00:01:25,917
games when it comes to being a competitive game.

21
00:01:26,537 --> 00:01:29,299
And I want to touch on some of the reasons why.

22
00:01:29,439 --> 00:01:33,622
So one of their innovations, maybe the main one, are the circular gems you can see on

23
00:01:33,662 --> 00:01:34,683
the left side of the screen.

24
00:01:35,483 --> 00:01:37,605
And when a red circle gem touches...

25
00:01:38,685 --> 00:01:41,386
other red gems, that is what breaks them and sends them to

26
00:01:41,406 --> 00:01:44,888
the other side. So it's not like a match three game where you

27
00:01:44,908 --> 00:01:47,129
get three reds that would automatically break. You're

28
00:01:47,149 --> 00:01:51,790
actually able to build up as big of a red gem as you want, and

29
00:01:52,391 --> 00:01:56,252
you can break that when you want by touching that circle gem to

30
00:01:56,332 --> 00:01:59,933
it. So what that does is it allows you to control the timing

31
00:02:00,034 --> 00:02:02,474
of your attacks as well as how big they are.

32
00:02:03,195 --> 00:02:07,918
That's on the offense side. On the defense side, when gems fall on the opponent's side of the

33
00:02:07,938 --> 00:02:15,223
screen, they don't fall randomly. They fall in a very predictable pattern. And it allows your

34
00:02:15,243 --> 00:02:19,886
opponent to build their side in a certain way so that they don't get too wrecked by your

35
00:02:19,986 --> 00:02:20,206
offense.

36
00:02:22,247 --> 00:02:24,129
So those two things together, that you can control

37
00:02:24,169 --> 00:02:26,391
the timing of your attacks and how big they are,

38
00:02:26,791 --> 00:02:29,013
and that defense really counts and matters,

39
00:02:29,794 --> 00:02:32,196
are sort of the basic elements that you would hope

40
00:02:32,276 --> 00:02:34,758
to have in a strategy game, and that's good,

41
00:02:34,818 --> 00:02:37,321
but that's not why this game is so memorable

42
00:02:37,401 --> 00:02:38,221
and so notable.

43
00:02:38,301 --> 00:02:39,863
The thing that's so unusual about it

44
00:02:39,943 --> 00:02:41,824
is actually its comeback mechanic.

45
00:02:42,505 --> 00:02:44,507
Comeback mechanics are common,

46
00:02:44,527 --> 00:02:45,528
and we see them in many games,

47
00:02:45,588 --> 00:02:47,830
but I haven't seen anything like how it works

48
00:02:48,350 --> 00:02:49,451
in this game anywhere else.

49
00:02:51,006 --> 00:02:51,807
So why is that?

50
00:02:51,867 --> 00:02:55,511
Well, when your side of the screen is almost full,

51
00:02:55,871 --> 00:02:57,192
that means that you've almost lost.

52
00:02:57,572 --> 00:03:00,415
But it also is when you're at your most powerful.

53
00:03:00,956 --> 00:03:02,817
And that's a crazy situation to be in,

54
00:03:02,857 --> 00:03:04,058
because when you're almost full,

55
00:03:04,098 --> 00:03:05,600
you're actually like right on the edge

56
00:03:05,780 --> 00:03:08,142
of winning and losing at the same time.

57
00:03:09,003 --> 00:03:09,523
So why is that?

58
00:03:09,603 --> 00:03:09,723
Well,

59
00:03:11,893 --> 00:03:15,333
partly because when your side is full, you have all the ammo,

60
00:03:15,494 --> 00:03:17,854
you have all these gems that you could potentially send to

61
00:03:17,874 --> 00:03:18,474
the other side.

62
00:03:18,534 --> 00:03:21,195
And you can realistically send them because of the way those

63
00:03:21,215 --> 00:03:22,135
circular gems work.

64
00:03:22,155 --> 00:03:25,435
You can kind of hide them here and there on your side of the

65
00:03:25,475 --> 00:03:25,775
screen.

66
00:03:26,796 --> 00:03:28,236
So you have a lot of ammo.

67
00:03:29,236 --> 00:03:30,396
You can realistically use it.

68
00:03:30,936 --> 00:03:32,517
And there's another rule called the height bonus.

69
00:03:32,537 --> 00:03:34,997
And what that says is that when gems are higher up on the

70
00:03:35,037 --> 00:03:37,158
screen, when you break them, they will send

71
00:03:37,498 --> 00:03:38,458
more to the opponent.

72
00:03:38,938 --> 00:03:41,138
So in other words, when you are about to lose, you have

73
00:03:41,759 --> 00:03:46,757
the most ammo and every shell of that ammo that you fire does more damage.

74
00:03:48,133 --> 00:03:50,995
The effect is so powerful that it's like a greed test.

75
00:03:51,056 --> 00:03:55,700
It's like how greedy do you want to be to get right up close to losing just so you can

76
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:58,963
be really powerful and send a ton to the opponent.

77
00:03:59,424 --> 00:04:04,349
There's another fun rule where if you send just a ton to the opponent, more than enough

78
00:04:04,389 --> 00:04:08,172
to fill their side of the screen, it doesn't drop on them instantly and end the game.

79
00:04:08,493 --> 00:04:11,896
Instead, it puts a number over their side of the screen and they have one more turn.

80
00:04:12,657 --> 00:04:17,778
that they can use to try to counteract that, to break gems on their side, to nullify what's

81
00:04:17,798 --> 00:04:25,159
going to fall. And taken together, what all this means, that you can control your offense,

82
00:04:25,199 --> 00:04:30,761
that there is pretty good defense, that being so close to winning and losing looks the same,

83
00:04:31,161 --> 00:04:38,142
is that a common dynamic that happens is like I almost beat you and fill you up really close

84
00:04:38,162 --> 00:04:41,923
to the top and then you're really powerful and you almost do it to me and then I ‑‑

85
00:04:42,936 --> 00:04:45,140
more than enough to fill your side,

86
00:04:45,160 --> 00:04:46,943
but you have that one more turn to stay back in

87
00:04:47,043 --> 00:04:48,485
and you dig yourself out.

88
00:04:48,525 --> 00:04:50,148
And there's this back and forth, back and forth,

89
00:04:50,649 --> 00:04:52,813
edge of the knife kind of gameplay.

90
00:04:53,957 --> 00:04:56,879
Where it's at any moment someone's gonna lose and it's so intense

91
00:04:58,199 --> 00:05:06,325
So that's it's very exciting and I played this game a ton. I've won a tournament in it in Chicago once I

