132
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:11,141
So I was just trying to sneak it into anything, just all the time.

133
00:07:12,902 --> 00:07:14,082
So it's no surprise.

134
00:07:14,102 --> 00:07:16,703
I was like, okay, there's not a lot of interaction here, what if it's like Puzzle Fighter?

135
00:07:18,104 --> 00:07:21,125
But then I started thinking, okay, what would that actually be like?

136
00:07:22,409 --> 00:07:25,650
Maybe this lines up, and then I was thinking about

137
00:07:25,710 --> 00:07:28,091
what I consider a good competitive game

138
00:07:28,131 --> 00:07:29,572
or some of the elements that I want.

139
00:07:30,032 --> 00:07:32,994
So I want a game, if it's gonna be a competitive game,

140
00:07:33,014 --> 00:07:34,394
to be highly interactive.

141
00:07:34,434 --> 00:07:35,895
I wanna interact with the opponent

142
00:07:36,496 --> 00:07:38,436
so that I can outplay the opponent,

143
00:07:38,476 --> 00:07:40,037
have the opportunity to do that,

144
00:07:40,357 --> 00:07:41,658
to predict what they're gonna do,

145
00:07:41,698 --> 00:07:42,779
to react what they're gonna do,

146
00:07:42,799 --> 00:07:44,940
to react what they did.

147
00:07:44,960 --> 00:07:45,000
So.

148
00:07:46,521 --> 00:07:49,182
I think there really needs to be as much interaction

149
00:07:49,603 --> 00:07:51,264
as possible for it to be skill testing.

150
00:07:51,744 --> 00:07:55,086
I also want hype, exciting moments built into the game,

151
00:07:55,126 --> 00:07:57,328
not something that's accidentally there,

152
00:07:57,428 --> 00:07:59,169
but all that stuff I told you about Puzzle Fighter,

153
00:07:59,269 --> 00:08:01,110
it's not an accident that it's so exciting.

154
00:08:01,130 --> 00:08:03,352
It comes directly from the rule design.

155
00:08:04,627 --> 00:08:06,849
I personally want games that are asymmetric,

156
00:08:06,909 --> 00:08:09,551
that means the kind where I choose a character

157
00:08:09,591 --> 00:08:10,853
and you choose a different character

158
00:08:10,893 --> 00:08:13,295
and we each have different strengths and weaknesses

159
00:08:13,415 --> 00:08:16,598
and now that's a matchup that has a certain dynamic

160
00:08:16,638 --> 00:08:18,480
of how it's played and we can switch characters

161
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:19,441
and have a different matchup.

162
00:08:19,541 --> 00:08:22,084
That's really interesting and really compelling to me

163
00:08:22,124 --> 00:08:23,105
so I knew I wanted that.

164
00:08:24,130 --> 00:08:28,872
And of course nobody would want a slow, boring start to their game.

165
00:08:29,132 --> 00:08:32,413
But it goes doubly so if you're making a competitive game,

166
00:08:32,473 --> 00:08:35,994
the kind that would ever be actually played in a competition,

167
00:08:36,034 --> 00:08:37,735
like if you're doing multiple rounds of Swiss,

168
00:08:37,795 --> 00:08:41,316
or if there's ever going to be commentary on it or something in streams.

169
00:08:42,137 --> 00:08:47,379
Every turn of the game really needs to pull its weight and be there for a reason.

170
00:08:47,539 --> 00:08:52,521
So you have to be careful about having kind of samey starts to your game all the time.

171
00:08:53,997 --> 00:08:56,278
So let me tell you a little bit about how Puzzle Strike,

172
00:08:56,318 --> 00:08:57,599
the tabletop game, works,

173
00:08:57,859 --> 00:09:00,900
and we can refer to these various points.

174
00:09:02,941 --> 00:09:04,562
This is a bit of a confusing diagram,

175
00:09:04,582 --> 00:09:06,083
but just bear with me.

176
00:09:06,203 --> 00:09:08,704
So in Puzzle Strike, you start with,

177
00:09:09,565 --> 00:09:12,446
well, each player has a zone called the gem pile,

178
00:09:12,486 --> 00:09:13,527
and that starts empty,

179
00:09:13,767 --> 00:09:15,908
and every turn you automatically will get

180
00:09:16,269 --> 00:09:17,829
one gem into your gem pile.

181
00:09:18,750 --> 00:09:22,035
and you lose the game if you ever end with 10 gems in your gem pile.

182
00:09:22,075 --> 00:09:25,780
So if nobody did anything, then after 10 turns, the game would end.

183
00:09:26,501 --> 00:09:29,244
There's a universal mechanic in the game called Combine,

184
00:09:29,264 --> 00:09:31,547
which is the upper left purple chip there.

185
00:09:31,568 --> 00:09:36,134
What that's showing is you can combine two of your 1 gems into a bigger 2 gem.

186
00:09:36,971 --> 00:09:39,692
There's another universal mechanic with the purple chip

187
00:09:39,992 --> 00:09:43,073
and the upper right, which is a crash gem.

188
00:09:43,733 --> 00:09:46,294
And what that's showing is that you can crash a two gem

189
00:09:46,674 --> 00:09:48,294
to break it apart into two ones

190
00:09:48,394 --> 00:09:50,695
and send those to the opponent's side.

191
00:09:51,075 --> 00:09:53,816
That diagram in the bottom middle is just showing

192
00:09:53,836 --> 00:09:55,617
that if you crash a three gem,

193
00:09:55,657 --> 00:09:56,737
it sends three to the opponent.

194
00:09:57,757 --> 00:10:02,419
So this concept of bundling up gems into a big gem

195
00:10:02,459 --> 00:10:04,079
and then crashing all of them to the opponent,

196
00:10:04,139 --> 00:10:05,700
that is offense.

197
00:10:07,154 --> 00:10:10,135
So what I mean by offense is that I said if nobody does

198
00:10:10,195 --> 00:10:11,756
anything, the game would end after 10 turns.

199
00:10:11,796 --> 00:10:14,958
But if I keep sending my gems to you, I'm reducing the

200
00:10:14,998 --> 00:10:15,539
number of turns.

201
00:10:15,579 --> 00:10:18,600
I'm trying to end the game quickly and fill your side up.

202
00:10:19,441 --> 00:10:20,281
So that's offense.

203
00:10:20,682 --> 00:10:23,683
Now defense is another mechanic called

204
00:10:23,864 --> 00:10:24,624
counter-crashing.

205
00:10:24,644 --> 00:10:29,107
And how that works, let's take the example that I have five

206
00:10:29,167 --> 00:10:31,348
gems in my gem pile, and you have five in yours.

207
00:10:32,008 --> 00:10:33,349
If I crash one gem.

208
00:10:34,210 --> 00:10:36,552
I'm going down to four, I'm sending one to you,

209
00:10:36,592 --> 00:10:37,793
and you're gonna go up to six.

210
00:10:38,794 --> 00:10:41,056
But if you counter crash, it's saying,

211
00:10:41,156 --> 00:10:43,939
hold on a minute, before that one gem arrives

212
00:10:44,099 --> 00:10:45,980
in my opponent's gem pile,

213
00:10:46,861 --> 00:10:49,083
they're gonna crash one of their own gems

214
00:10:49,564 --> 00:10:52,987
and send it not at me, but at the incoming gem.

215
00:10:53,027 --> 00:10:54,688
So it's like I'm firing a missile

216
00:10:54,728 --> 00:10:55,629
and they're shooting it down.

217
00:10:56,577 --> 00:10:59,118
And those gems that meet in the air

218
00:10:59,278 --> 00:11:00,618
are removed from the system.

219
00:11:01,299 --> 00:11:04,960
So that's defense, because it's slowing the game down,

220
00:11:05,120 --> 00:11:06,201
adding turns to the game.

221
00:11:06,441 --> 00:11:09,142
In this example here, my opponent didn't go

222
00:11:09,802 --> 00:11:12,604
from five to six, they actually went from five to four.

223
00:11:12,864 --> 00:11:15,505
They got farther away from that lose condition.

224
00:11:16,885 --> 00:11:18,366
So that's offense and defense.

225
00:11:20,611 --> 00:11:28,262
Since I'm covering those I think it's important to mention kind of the third leg of the triangle which is economy and when I think of

226
00:11:29,263 --> 00:11:33,890
These these three concepts I think of Starcraft which is depicted in this cake

227
00:11:35,913 --> 00:11:40,980
So in Starcraft, offense is like I build units and send them to your base right away.

228
00:11:41,460 --> 00:11:48,670
Defense is something like if the opponent is a Terran, they might build bunkers, which

229
00:11:48,710 --> 00:11:49,591
is static defense.

230
00:11:49,631 --> 00:11:52,695
It doesn't move around, but it's very effective against early attackers.

231
00:11:53,496 --> 00:11:56,718
But what do you do against someone who is playing defensive?

232
00:11:57,698 --> 00:12:02,421
There's really no point in attacking them early because you're sort of wasting your early units.

233
00:12:02,981 --> 00:12:06,543
And you also don't need to play defensively yourself because they're not threatening you.

234
00:12:07,063 --> 00:12:08,344
You can sort of do whatever you want.

235
00:12:08,664 --> 00:12:11,705
So what's best to do in Starcraft is to invest in your economy.

236
00:12:12,506 --> 00:12:15,587
And by doing that, a little bit later in the game you can have so much money.

237
00:12:16,767 --> 00:12:23,850
you can kind of do anything. So economy beats defense. And in the course of a game of Starcraft,

238
00:12:24,110 --> 00:12:28,852
there's a dance between offense, defense, and economy where you're kind of going back

239
00:12:28,892 --> 00:12:32,893
and forth between them depending on what the opponent does. And that same exact sort of

240
00:12:32,913 --> 00:12:38,396
thing is going on in the tabletop game Puzzle Strike. So the first item on my list was I

